description.narrative: By 2017, children associated with armed forces and armed groups, including self-defense groups, are released and recevive a multi- sectoral support for their rehabilitation and reintegration into their families and communities., which contributes to Child Protection And Emergencies, Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: The capacity of institutional and non-institutional protection actors is enhanced at the national and regional levels to enable them to provide gender-sensitive medical, psychosocial, legal, and livelihoods support and life skills training to vulnerable and sexually abused women and girls.

description.narrative: 2,969 children associated with armed groups, including 834 girls were assisted by UNICEF partners. 2,189 children including 898 girls benefited from a community reintegration program. The decreased of funding impacted socio-economic reintegration of the released children. 37% of these children since 2014 are awaiting for socio-economic support. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:14/01/2018
